title: Top executives

title: Chief executives
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Top executives/Chief executives/NA
Def: Determine and formulate policies and provide overall direction of companies or private and public sector organizations within guidelines set up by a board of directors or similar governing body. Plan, direct, or coordinate operational activities at the highest level of management with the help of subordinate executives and staff managers.

title: General & operations managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Top executives/General & operations managers/NA
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate the operations of public or private sector organizations, overseeing multiple departments or locations. Duties and responsibilities include formulating policies, managing daily operations, and planning the use of materials and human resources, but are too diverse and general in nature to be classified in any one functional area of management or administration, such as personnel, purchasing, or administrative services. Usually manage through subordinate supervisors. Excludes First-Line Supervisors.

title: Legislators
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Top executives/Legislators/NA
Def: Develop, introduce, or enact laws and statutes at the local, tribal, state, or federal level. Includes only workers in elected positions.

title: Advertising, marketing, promotions, public relations, & sales managers
Level3: Advertising, marketing, promotions, public relations, & sales managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Advertising, marketing, etc/Advertising, marketing, promotions, public relations, & sales managers/NA

title: Advertising & promotions managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Advertising, marketing, etc/Advertising & promotions managers/NA
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate advertising policies and programs or produce collateral materials, such as posters, contests, coupons, or giveaways, to create extra interest in the purchase of a product or service for a department, an entire organization, or on an account basis.

title: Marketing & sales managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Advertising, marketing, etc/Marketing & sales managers/NA

title: Marketing managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Advertising, marketing, etc/Marketing & sales managers/Marketing managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate marketing policies and programs, such as determining the demand for products and services offered by a firm and its competitors, and identify potential customers. Develop pricing strategies with the goal of maximizing the firm’s profits or share of the market while ensuring the firm’s customers are satisfied. Oversee product development or monitor trends that indicate the need for new products and services.

title: Sales managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Advertising, marketing, etc/Marketing & sales managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate the actual distribution or movement of a product or service to the customer. Coordinate sales distribution by establishing sales territories, quotas, and goals and establish training programs for sales representatives. Analyze sales statistics gathered by staff to determine sales potential and inventory requirements and monitor the preferences of customers.

title: Public relations & fundraising managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Advertising, marketing, etc/Public relations & fundraising managers/Sales managers

title: Operations specialties managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Public relations & fundraising managers/Sales managers

title: Administrative services managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Administrative services managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate one or more administrative services of an organization, such as records and information management, mail distribution, and other office support services. Medical records administrators are included in “Medical and Health Services Managers” (11-9111). Excludes “Facilities Managers” (11-3013) and “Purchasing Managers” (11-3061).

title: Computer & information systems managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Computer & information systems managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate activities in such fields as electronic data processing, information systems, systems analysis, and computer programming. Excludes “Computer Occupations” (15-1211 through 15-1299).

title: Financial managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Financial managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate accounting, investing, banking, insurance, securities, and other financial activities of a branch, office, or department of an establishment. Excludes “Financial Risk Specialists” (13-2054).

title: Industrial production managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Industrial production managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate the work activities and resources necessary for manufacturing products in accordance with cost, quality, and quantity specifications.

title: Purchasing managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Purchasing managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate the activities of buyers, purchasing officers, and related workers involved in purchasing materials, products, and services. Includes wholesale or retail trade merchandising managers and procurement managers.

title: Transportation, storage, & distribution managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Transportation, storage, etc/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate transportation, storage, or distribution activities in accordance with organizational policies and applicable government laws or regulations. Includes logistics managers.

title: Compensation & benefits managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Compensation & benefits managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate compensation and benefits activities of an organization. Job analysis and position description managers are included in “Human Resources Managers” (11-3121).

title: Human resources managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Human resources managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate human resources activities and staff of an organization. Excludes managers who primarily focus on compensation and benefits (11-3111) and training and development (11-3131).

title: Training & development managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Operations specialties managers/Training & development managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate the training and development activities and staff of an organization.

title: Other management occupations
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Training & development managers/Sales managers

title: Farmers, ranchers, & other agricultural managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Farmers, ranchers, etc/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate the management or operation of farms, ranches, greenhouses, aquacultural operations, nurseries, timber tracts, or other agricultural establishments. May hire, train, and supervise farm workers or contract for services to carry out the day-to-day activities of the managed operation. May engage in or supervise planting, cultivating, harvesting, and financial and marketing activities. Excludes “First-Line Supervisors of Farming, Fishing, and Forestry Workers” (45-1011).

title: Construction managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Construction managers/Sales managers
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate, usually through subordinate supervisory personnel, activities concerned with the construction and maintenance of structures, facilities, and systems. Participate in the conceptual development of a construction project and oversee its organization, scheduling, budgeting, and implementation. Includes managers in specialized construction fields, such as carpentry or plumbing.

title: Education administrators
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Education administrators/Sales managers

title: Education administrators, preschool & childcare center/program
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Education administrators/Education administrators, preschool & childcare center/program

title: Education administrators, elementary & secondary school
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Education administrators/Education administrators, elementary & secondary school

title: Education administrators, postsecondary
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Education administrators/Education administrators, postsecondary
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate student instruction, administration, and services, as well as other research and educational activities, at postsecondary institutions, including universities, colleges, and junior and community colleges.

title: Education administrators, all other
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Education administrators/Education administrators, all other
Def: All education administrators not listed separately.

title: Architectural & engineering managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Architectural & engineering managers/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate activities in such fields as architecture and engineering or research and development in these fields. Excludes “Natural Sciences Managers” (11-9121).

title: Food service managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Food service managers/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate activities of an organization or department that serves food and beverages. Excludes “Chefs and Head Cooks” (35-1011).

title: Funeral service managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Funeral service managers/Education administrators, all other

title: Gaming managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Gaming managers/Education administrators, all other

title: Lodging managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Lodging managers/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate activities of an organization or department that provides lodging and other accommodations. Excludes “Food Service Managers” (11-9051) in lodging establishments.

title: Medical & health services managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Medical & health services managers/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate medical and health services in hospitals, clinics, managed care organizations, public health agencies, or similar organizations.

title: Natural sciences managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Natural sciences managers/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate activities in such fields as life sciences, physical sciences, mathematics, statistics, and research and development in these fields. Excludes “Computer and Information Systems Managers” (11-3021) and “Architecture and Engineering Managers” (11-9041).

title: Postmasters & mail superintendents
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Postmasters & mail superintendents/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate operational, administrative, management, and support services of a U.S. post office; or coordinate activities of workers engaged in postal and related work in assigned post office.

title: Property, real estate, & community association managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Property, real estate, etc/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate the selling, buying, leasing, or governance activities of commercial, industrial, or residential real estate properties. Includes managers of homeowner and condominium associations, rented or leased housing units, buildings, or land (including rights-of-way).

title: Social & community service managers
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Social & community service managers/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan, direct, or coordinate the activities of a social service program or community outreach organization. Oversee the program or organization’s budget and policies regarding participant involvement, program requirements, and benefits. Work may involve directing social workers, counselors, or probation officers.

title: Emergency management directors
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Emergency management directors/Education administrators, all other
Def: Plan and direct disaster response or crisis management activities, provide disaster preparedness training, and prepare emergency plans and procedures for natural (e.g., hurricanes, floods, earthquakes), wartime, or technological (e.g., nuclear power plant emergencies or hazardous materials spills) disasters or hostage situations.

title: Managers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Management occupations/Other management occupations/Managers, all other/Education administrators, all other
Def: All managers not listed separately.

title: Business & financial operations occupations
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Other management occupations/Managers, all other/Education administrators, all other

title: Business operations specialists
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Managers, all other/Education administrators, all other

title: Agents & business managers of artists, performers, & athletes
ttl: Agents & business managers of artists, performers, etc
Level3: Agents & business managers of artists, performers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Agents & business managers of artists, performers, etc/Education administrators, all other
Def: Represent and promote artists, performers, and athletes in dealings with current or prospective employers. May handle contract negotiation and other business matters for clients.

title: Buyers & purchasing agents
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Buyers & purchasing agents/Education administrators, all other

title: Buyers & purchasing agents, farm products
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Buyers & purchasing agents/Buyers & purchasing agents, farm products
Def: Purchase farm products either for further processing or resale. Includes tree farm contractors, grain brokers and market operators, grain buyers, and tobacco buyers. May negotiate contracts.

title: Wholesale & retail buyers, except farm products
ttl: Wholesale & retail buyers, except farm products
Level4: Wholesale & retail buyers, except farm products
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Buyers & purchasing agents/Wholesale & retail buyers, except farm products
Def: Buy merchandise or commodities, other than farm products, for resale to consumers at the wholesale or retail level, including both durable and nondurable goods. Analyze past buying trends, sales records, price, and quality of merchandise to determine value and yield. Select, order, and authorize payment for merchandise according to contractual agreements. May conduct meetings with sales personnel and introduce new products. May negotiate contracts. Includes assistant wholesale and retail buyers of nonfarm products. Excludes “Procurement Clerks” (43-3061).

title: Purchasing agents, except wholesale, retail, & farm products
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Buyers & purchasing agents/Purchasing agents, except wholesale, etc
Def: Purchase machinery, equipment, tools, parts, supplies, or services necessary for the operation of an establishment. Purchase raw or semifinished materials for manufacturing. May negotiate contracts. Excludes “Buyers and Purchasing Agents, Farm Products” (13-1021) and “Wholesale and Retail Buyers, Except Farm Products” (13-1022).

title: Claims adjusters, appraisers, examiners, & investigators
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Claims adjusters, appraisers, etc/Purchasing agents, except wholesale, etc

title: Claims adjusters, examiners, & investigators
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Claims adjusters, appraisers, etc/Claims adjusters, examiners, etc
Def: Review settled claims to determine that payments and settlements are made in accordance with company practices and procedures. Confer with legal counsel on claims requiring litigation. May also settle insurance claims. Excludes “Fire Inspectors and Investigators” (33-2021).

title: Insurance appraisers, auto damage
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Claims adjusters, appraisers, etc/Insurance appraisers, auto damage
Def: Appraise automobile or other vehicle damage to determine repair costs for insurance claim settlement. Prepare insurance forms to indicate repair cost or cost estimates and recommendations. May seek agreement with automotive repair shop on repair costs.

title: Compliance officers
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Compliance officers/Insurance appraisers, auto damage
Def: Examine, evaluate, and investigate eligibility for or conformity with laws and regulations governing contract compliance of licenses and permits, and perform other compliance and enforcement inspection and analysis activities not classified elsewhere. Excludes “Financial Examiners" (13-2061), “Tax Examiners and Collectors, and Revenue Agents” (13-2081), “Occupational Health and Safety Specialists” (19-5011), “Occupational Health and Safety Technicians” (19-5012), “Transportation Security Screeners” (33-9093), “Agricultural Inspectors” (45-2011), “Construction and Building Inspectors” (47-4011), and “Transportation Inspectors” (53-6051).

title: Cost estimators
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Cost estimators/Insurance appraisers, auto damage
Def: Prepare cost estimates for product manufacturing, construction projects, or services to aid management in bidding on or determining price of product or service. May specialize according to particular service performed or type of product manufactured.

title: Human resources workers
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Human resources workers/Insurance appraisers, auto damage

title: Human resources specialists
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Human resources workers/Human resources specialists
Def: Recruit, screen, interview, or place individuals within an organization. May perform other activities in multiple human resources areas. Excludes “Compensation, Benefits, and Job Analysis Specialists” (13-1141) and “Training and Development Specialists” (13-1151).

title: Farm labor contractors
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Human resources workers/Farm labor contractors
Def: Recruit and hire seasonal or temporary agricultural laborers. May transport, house, and provide meals for workers.

title: Labor relations specialists
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Human resources workers/Labor relations specialists
Def: Resolve disputes between workers and managers, negotiate collective bargaining agreements, or coordinate grievance procedures to handle employee complaints. Excludes equal employment opportunity (EEO) officers, who are included in “Compliance Officers” (13-1041).

title: Logisticians
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Logisticians/Labor relations specialists
Def: Analyze and coordinate the ongoing logistical functions of a firm or organization. Responsible for the entire life cycle of a product, including acquisition, distribution, internal allocation, delivery, and final disposal of resources. Excludes “Transportation, Storage, and Distribution Managers” (11-3071) and “Project Management Specialists” (13-1082).

title: Management analysts
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Management analysts/Labor relations specialists
Def: Conduct organizational studies and evaluations, design systems and procedures, conduct work simplification and measurement studies, and prepare operations and procedures manuals to assist management in operating more efficiently and effectively. Includes program analysts and management consultants. Excludes “Computer Systems Analysts” (15-1211) and “Operations Research Analysts” (15-2031).

title: Meeting, convention, & event planners
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Meeting, convention, etc/Labor relations specialists
Def: Coordinate activities of staff, convention personnel, or clients to make arrangements for group meetings, events, or conventions.

title: Fundraisers
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Fundraisers/Labor relations specialists
Def: Organize activities to raise funds or otherwise solicit and gather monetary donations or other gifts for an organization. May design and produce promotional materials. May also raise awareness of the organization’s work, goals, and financial needs.

title: Compensation, benefits, & job analysis specialists
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Compensation, benefits, etc/Labor relations specialists
Def: Conduct programs of compensation and benefits and job analysis for employer. May specialize in specific areas, such as position classification and pension programs.

title: Training & development specialists
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Training & development specialists/Labor relations specialists
Def: Design or conduct work-related training and development programs to improve individual skills or organizational performance. May analyze organizational training needs or evaluate training effectiveness. Excludes “Career/Technical Education Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1194) and “Other Teachers and Instructors” (25-3000). Flight instructors are included with “Aircraft Pilots and Flight Engineers” (53-2010).

title: Market research analysts & marketing specialists
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Market research analysts & marketing specialists/Labor relations specialists
Def: Research conditions in local, regional, national, or online markets. Gather information to determine potential sales of a product or service, or plan a marketing or advertising campaign. May gather information on competitors, prices, sales, and methods of marketing and distribution. May employ search marketing tactics, analyze web metrics, and develop recommendations to increase search engine ranking and visibility to target markets. Excludes “Web and Digital Interface Designers” (15-1255), “Art Directors” (27-1011), “Graphic Designers” (27-1024), and “Public Relations Specialists” (27-3031).

title: Business operations specialists, all other
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Business operations specialists/Business operations specialists, all other/Labor relations specialists
Def: All business operations specialists not listed separately.

title: Financial specialists
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Business operations specialists, all other/Labor relations specialists

title: Accountants & auditors
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Accountants & auditors/Labor relations specialists
Def: Examine, analyze, and interpret accounting records to prepare financial statements, give advice, or audit and evaluate statements prepared by others. Install or advise on systems of recording costs or other financial and budgetary data. Excludes “Tax Examiners and Collectors, and Revenue Agents” (13-2081).

title: Appraisers & assessors of real estate
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Appraisers & assessors of real estate/Labor relations specialists
Def: Appraise real estate, exclusively, and estimate its fair value. May assess taxes in accordance with prescribed schedules. Excludes “Appraisers of Personal and Business Property” (13-2022).

title: Budget analysts
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Budget analysts/Labor relations specialists
Def: Examine budget estimates for completeness, accuracy, and conformance with procedures and regulations. Analyze budgeting and accounting reports. Excludes “Financial and Investment Analysts” (13-2051).

title: Credit analysts
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Credit analysts/Labor relations specialists
Def: Analyze credit data and financial statements of individuals or firms to determine the degree of risk involved in extending credit or lending money. Prepare reports with credit information for use in decisionmaking. Excludes “Financial Risk Specialists” (13-2054).

title: Financial analysts & advisors
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Financial analysts & advisors/Labor relations specialists

title: Financial analysts
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Financial analysts & advisors/Financial analysts

title: Personal financial advisors
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Financial analysts & advisors/Personal financial advisors
Def: Advise clients on financial plans using knowledge of tax and investment strategies, securities, insurance, pension plans, and real estate. Duties include assessing clients' assets, liabilities, cash flow, insurance coverage, tax status, and financial objectives. May also buy and sell financial assets for clients. Excludes “Securities, Commodities, and Financial Services Sales Agents” (41-3031).

title: Insurance underwriters
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Financial analysts & advisors/Insurance underwriters
Def: Review individual applications for insurance to evaluate degree of risk involved and determine acceptance of applications.

title: Financial examiners
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Financial examiners/Insurance underwriters
Def: Enforce or ensure compliance with laws and regulations governing financial and securities institutions and financial and real estate transactions. May examine, verify, or authenticate records.

title: Credit counselors & loan officers
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Credit counselors & loan officers/Insurance underwriters

title: Credit counselors
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Credit counselors & loan officers/Credit counselors
Def: Advise and educate individuals or organizations on acquiring and managing debt. May provide guidance in determining the best type of loan and explain loan requirements or restrictions. May help develop debt management plans or student financial aid packages. May advise on credit issues, or provide budget, mortgage, bankruptcy, or student financial aid counseling.

title: Loan officers
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Credit counselors & loan officers/Loan officers
Def: Evaluate, authorize, or recommend approval of commercial, real estate, or credit loans. Advise borrowers on financial status and payment methods. Includes mortgage loan officers and agents, collection analysts, loan servicing officers, loan underwriters, and payday loan officers.

title: Tax examiners, collectors & preparers, & revenue agents
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Tax examiners, collectors & preparers, etc/Loan officers

title: Tax examiners & collectors, & revenue agents
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Tax examiners, collectors & preparers, etc/Tax examiners & collectors, & revenue agents
Def: Determine tax liability or collect taxes from individuals or business firms according to prescribed laws and regulations.

title: Tax preparers
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Tax examiners, collectors & preparers, etc/Tax preparers
Def: Prepare tax returns for individuals or small businesses. Excludes “Accountants and Auditors” (13-2011).

title: Financial specialists, all other
pathString: Jobs/Business & financial operations occupations/Financial specialists/Financial specialists, all other/Tax preparers
Def: All financial specialists not listed separately.

title: Computer & mathematical occupations
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Financial specialists/Financial specialists, all other/Tax preparers

title: Computer occupations
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Financial specialists, all other/Tax preparers

title: Computer & information research scientists
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Computer & information research scientists/Tax preparers
Def: Conduct research into fundamental computer and information science as theorists, designers, or inventors. Develop solutions to problems in the field of computer hardware and software.

title: Computer & information analysts
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Computer & information analysts/Tax preparers

title: Computer systems analysts
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Computer & information analysts/Computer systems analysts
Def: Analyze science, engineering, business, and other data processing problems to develop and implement solutions to complex applications problems, system administration issues, or network concerns. Perform systems management and integration functions, improve existing computer systems, and review computer system capabilities, workflow, and schedule limitations. May analyze or recommend commercially available software.

title: Information security analysts
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Computer & information analysts/Information security analysts
Def: Plan, implement, upgrade, or monitor security measures for the protection of computer networks and information. Assess system vulnerabilities for security risks and propose and implement risk mitigation strategies. May ensure appropriate security controls are in place that will safeguard digital files and vital electronic infrastructure. May respond to computer security breaches and viruses. Excludes “Computer Network Architects” (15-1241).

title: Software developers & programmers
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Software developers & programmers/Information security analysts

title: Computer programmers
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Software developers & programmers/Computer programmers
Def: Create, modify, and test the code and scripts that allow computer applications to run. Work from specifications drawn up by software and web developers or other individuals. May develop and write computer programs to store, locate, and retrieve specific documents, data, and information.

title: Software developers, applications
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Software developers & programmers/Software developers, applications

title: Software developers, systems software
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Software developers & programmers/Software developers, systems software

title: Web developers
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Software developers & programmers/Web developers
Def: Develop and implement websites, web applications, application databases, and interactive web interfaces. Evaluate code to ensure that it is properly structured, meets industry standards, and is compatible with browsers and devices. Optimize website performance, scalability, and server-side code and processes. May develop website infrastructure and integrate websites with other computer applications. Excludes “Special Effects Artists and Animators” (27-1014).

title: Database & systems administrators & network architects
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Database & systems administrators & network architects/Web developers

title: Database administrators
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Database & systems administrators & network architects/Database administrators
Def: Administer, test, and implement computer databases, applying knowledge of database management systems. Coordinate changes to computer databases. Identify, investigate, and resolve database performance issues, database capacity, and database scalability. May plan, coordinate, and implement security measures to safeguard computer databases. Excludes “Information Security Analysts” (15-1212) and “Database Architects” (15-1243).

title: Network & computer systems administrators
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Database & systems administrators & network architects/Network & computer systems administrators
Def: Install, configure, and maintain an organization’s local area network (LAN), wide area network (WAN), data communications network, operating systems, and physical and virtual servers. Perform system monitoring and verify the integrity and availability of hardware, network, and server resources and systems. Review system and application logs and verify completion of scheduled jobs, including system backups. Analyze network and server resource consumption and control user access. Install and upgrade software and maintain software licenses. May assist in network modeling, analysis, planning, and coordination between network and data communications hardware and software. Excludes “Information Security Analysts” (15-1212), “Computer Network Support Specialists” (15-1231), and “Computer User Support Specialists” (15-1232).

title: Computer network architects
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Database & systems administrators & network architects/Computer network architects
Def: Design and implement computer and information networks, such as local area networks (LAN), wide area networks (WAN), intranets, extranets, and other data communications networks. Perform network modeling, analysis, and planning, including analysis of capacity needs for network infrastructures. May also design network and computer security measures. May research and recommend network and data communications hardware and software. Excludes “Information Security Analysts” (15-1212), “Computer Network Support Specialists” (15-1231), and “Network and Computer Systems Administrators” (15-1244).

title: Computer support specialists
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Computer support specialists/Computer network architects

title: Computer user support specialists
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Computer support specialists/Computer user support specialists
Def: Provide technical assistance to computer users. Answer questions or resolve computer problems for clients in person, via telephone, or electronically. May provide assistance concerning the use of computer hardware and software, including printing, installation, word processing, electronic mail, and operating systems. Excludes “Network and Computer Systems Administrators” (15-1244).

title: Computer network support specialists
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Computer support specialists/Computer network support specialists
Def: Analyze, test, troubleshoot, and evaluate existing network systems, such as local area networks (LAN), wide area networks (WAN), cloud networks, servers, and other data communications networks. Perform network maintenance to ensure networks operate correctly with minimal interruption. Excludes “Computer Network Architects” (15-1241) and “Network and Computer Systems Administrators” (15-1244).

title: Computer occupations, all other
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Computer occupations/Computer occupations, all other/Computer network support specialists
Def: All computer occupations not listed separately. Excludes “Computer and Information Systems Managers” (11-3021), “Computer Hardware Engineers” (17-2061), “Electrical and Electronics Engineers” (17-2070), “Computer Science Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1021), “Special Effects Artists and Animators” (27-1014), “Graphic Designers” (27-1024), “Health Information Technologists and Medical Registrars” (29-9021), and “Computer, Automated Teller, and Office Machine Repairers” (49-2011).

title: Mathematical science occupations
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Mathematical science occupations/Computer occupations, all other/Computer network support specialists

title: Actuaries
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Mathematical science occupations/Actuaries/Computer network support specialists
Def: Analyze statistical data, such as mortality, accident, sickness, disability, and retirement rates and construct probability tables to forecast risk and liability for payment of future benefits. May ascertain insurance rates required and cash reserves necessary to ensure payment of future benefits.

title: Mathematicians
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Mathematical science occupations/Mathematicians/Computer network support specialists
Def: Conduct research in fundamental mathematics or in application of mathematical techniques to science, management, and other fields. Solve problems in various fields using mathematical methods.

title: Operations research analysts
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Mathematical science occupations/Operations research analysts/Computer network support specialists
Def: Formulate and apply mathematical modeling and other optimizing methods to develop and interpret information that assists management with decisionmaking, policy formulation, or other managerial functions. May collect and analyze data and develop decision support software, services, or products. May develop and supply optimal time, cost, or logistics networks for program evaluation, review, or implementation.

title: Statisticians
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Mathematical science occupations/Statisticians/Computer network support specialists
Def: Develop or apply mathematical or statistical theory and methods to collect, organize, interpret, and summarize numerical data to provide usable information. May specialize in fields such as biostatistics, agricultural statistics, business statistics, or economic statistics. Includes mathematical and survey statisticians. Excludes “Survey Researchers” (19-3022).

title: Miscellaneous mathematical science occupations
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Mathematical science occupations/Miscellaneous mathematical science occupations/Computer network support specialists

pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Mathematical science occupations/Miscellaneous mathematical science occupations/Mathematical technicians

title: Mathematical science occupations, all other
pathString: Jobs/Computer & mathematical occupations/Mathematical science occupations/Miscellaneous mathematical science occupations/Mathematical science occupations, all other
Def: All mathematical scientists not listed separately.

title: Surveyors, cartographers, & photogrammetrists

title: Cartographers & photogrammetrists
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Architects, surveyors, etc/Surveyors, cartographers, etc/Cartographers & photogrammetrists
Def: Research, study, and prepare maps and other spatial data in digital or graphic form for one or more purposes, such as legal, social, political, educational, and design purposes. May work with Geographic Information Systems (GIS). May design and evaluate algorithms, data structures, and user interfaces for GIS and mapping systems. May collect, analyze, and interpret geographic information provided by geodetic surveys, aerial photographs, and satellite data.

title: Surveyors
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Architects, surveyors, etc/Surveyors, cartographers, etc/Surveyors
Def: Make exact measurements and determine property boundaries. Provide data relevant to the shape, contour, gravitation, location, elevation, or dimension of land or land features on or near the earth’s surface for engineering, mapmaking, mining, land evaluation, construction, and other purposes.

title: Engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Surveyors, cartographers, etc/Surveyors

title: Aerospace engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Aerospace engineers/Surveyors
Def: Perform engineering duties in designing, constructing, and testing aircraft, missiles, and spacecraft. May conduct basic and applied research to evaluate adaptability of materials and equipment to aircraft design and manufacture. May recommend improvements in testing equipment and techniques.

title: Agricultural engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Agricultural engineers/Surveyors
Def: Apply knowledge of engineering technology and biological science to agricultural problems concerned with power and machinery, electrification, structures, soil and water conservation, and processing of agricultural products.

title: Biomedical engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Biomedical engineers/Surveyors

title: Chemical engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Chemical engineers/Surveyors
Def: Design chemical plant equipment and devise processes for manufacturing chemicals and products, such as gasoline, synthetic rubber, plastics, detergents, cement, paper, and pulp, by applying principles and technology of chemistry, physics, and engineering.

title: Civil engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Civil engineers/Surveyors
Def: Perform engineering duties in planning, designing, and overseeing construction and maintenance of building structures and facilities, such as roads, railroads, airports, bridges, harbors, channels, dams, irrigation projects, pipelines, power plants, and water and sewage systems. Includes architectural, structural, traffic, and geotechnical engineers. Excludes “Hydrologists” (19-2043).

title: Computer hardware engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Computer hardware engineers/Surveyors
Def: Research, design, develop, or test computer or computer-related equipment for commercial, industrial, military, or scientific use. May supervise the manufacturing and installation of computer or computer-related equipment and components. Excludes “Software Developers” (15-1252) and “Web Developers” (15-1254).

title: Electrical & electronics engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Electrical & electronics engineers/Surveyors

title: Electrical engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Electrical & electronics engineers/Electrical engineers
Def: Research, design, develop, test, or supervise the manufacturing and installation of electrical equipment, components, or systems for commercial, industrial, military, or scientific use. Excludes “Computer Hardware Engineers” (17-2061).

title: Electronics engineers, except computer
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Electrical & electronics engineers/Electronics engineers, except computer
Def: Research, design, develop, or test electronic components and systems for commercial, industrial, military, or scientific use employing knowledge of electronic theory and materials properties. Design electronic circuits and components for use in fields such as telecommunications, aerospace guidance and propulsion control, acoustics, or instruments and controls. Excludes “Computer Hardware Engineers” (17-2061).

title: Environmental engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Environmental engineers/Electronics engineers, except computer
Def: Research, design, plan, or perform engineering duties in the prevention, control, and remediation of environmental hazards using various engineering disciplines. Work may include waste treatment, site remediation, or pollution control technology.

title: Industrial engineers, including health & safety
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Industrial engineers, including health & safety/Electronics engineers, except computer

title: Health & safety engineers, except mining safety engineers & inspectors
ttl: Health & safety engineers, except mining safety engineers & inspectors
Level4: Health & safety engineers, except mining safety engineers & inspectors
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Industrial engineers, including health & safety/Health & safety engineers, except mining safety engineers & inspectors
Def: Promote worksite or product safety by applying knowledge of industrial processes, mechanics, chemistry, psychology, and industrial health and safety laws. Includes industrial product safety engineers.

title: Industrial engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Industrial engineers, including health & safety/Industrial engineers
Def: Design, develop, test, and evaluate integrated systems for managing industrial production processes, including human work factors, quality control, inventory control, logistics and material flow, cost analysis, and production coordination. Excludes “Health and Safety Engineers, Except Mining Safety Engineers and Inspectors” (17-2111).

title: Marine engineers & naval architects
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Marine engineers & naval architects/Industrial engineers
Def: Design, develop, and evaluate the operation of marine vessels, ship machinery, and related equipment, such as power supply and propulsion systems.

title: Materials engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Materials engineers/Industrial engineers
Def: Evaluate materials and develop machinery and processes to manufacture materials for use in products that must meet specialized design and performance specifications. Develop new uses for known materials. Includes those engineers working with composite materials or specializing in one type of material, such as graphite, metal and metal alloys, ceramics and glass, plastics and polymers, and naturally occurring materials. Includes metallurgists and metallurgical engineers, ceramic engineers, and welding engineers.

title: Mechanical engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Mechanical engineers/Industrial engineers
Def: Perform engineering duties in planning and designing tools, engines, machines, and other mechanically functioning equipment. Oversee installation, operation, maintenance, and repair of equipment such as centralized heat, gas, water, and steam systems.

title: Mining & geological engineers, including mining safety engineers
ttl: Mining & geological engineers, including mining safety engineers
Level3: Mining & geological engineers, including mining safety engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Mining & geological engineers, including mining safety engineers/Industrial engineers
Def: Conduct subsurface surveys to identify the characteristics of potential land or mining development sites. May specify the ground support systems, processes, and equipment for safe, economical, and environmentally sound extraction or underground construction activities. May inspect areas for unsafe geological conditions, equipment, and working conditions. May design, implement, and coordinate mine safety programs. Excludes “Petroleum Engineers” (17-2171).

title: Nuclear engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Nuclear engineers/Industrial engineers
Def: Conduct research on nuclear engineering projects or apply principles and theory of nuclear science to problems concerned with release, control, and use of nuclear energy and nuclear waste disposal.

title: Petroleum engineers
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Petroleum engineers/Industrial engineers
Def: Devise methods to improve oil and gas extraction and production and determine the need for new or modified tool designs. Oversee drilling and offer technical advice.

title: Engineers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Engineers/Engineers, all other/Industrial engineers
Def: All engineers not listed separately. Excludes “Sales Engineers” (41-9031), “Locomotive Engineers” (53-4011), and “Ship Engineers” (53-5031).

title: Drafters, engineering technicians, & mapping technicians

title: Drafters
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Drafters/Industrial engineers

title: Architectural & civil drafters
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Drafters/Architectural & civil drafters
Def: Prepare detailed drawings of architectural and structural features of buildings or drawings and topographical relief maps used in civil engineering projects, such as highways, bridges, and public works. Use knowledge of building materials, engineering practices, and mathematics to complete drawings.

title: Electrical & electronics drafters
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Drafters/Electrical & electronics drafters
Def: Prepare wiring diagrams, circuit board assembly diagrams, and layout drawings used for the manufacture, installation, or repair of electrical equipment.

title: Mechanical drafters
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Drafters/Mechanical drafters
Def: Prepare detailed working diagrams of machinery and mechanical devices, including dimensions, fastening methods, and other engineering information.

title: Drafters, all other
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Drafters/Drafters, all other
Def: All drafters not listed separately.

pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Engineering technicians, except drafters/Aerospace engineering & operations technicians

pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Engineering technicians, except drafters/Civil engineering technicians

pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Engineering technicians, except drafters/Electrical & electronics engineering technicians

pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Engineering technicians, except drafters/Mechanical engineering technicians

title: Surveying & mapping technicians
pathString: Jobs/Architecture & engineering occupations/Drafters, engineering technicians, etc/Surveying & mapping technicians/Engineering technicians, except drafters, etc
Def: Perform surveying and mapping duties, usually under the direction of an engineer, surveyor, cartographer, or photogrammetrist, to obtain data used for construction, mapmaking, boundary location, mining, or other purposes. May calculate mapmaking information and create maps from source data, such as surveying notes, aerial photography, satellite data, or other maps to show topographical features, political boundaries, and other features. May verify accuracy and completeness of maps. Excludes “Cartographers and Photogrammetrists” (17-1021), “Surveyors" (17-1022), and “Geoscientists, Except Hydrologists and Geographers” (19-2042).

title: Life scientists

title: Agricultural & food scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Agricultural & food scientists/Engineering technicians, except drafters, etc

title: Animal scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Agricultural & food scientists/Animal scientists
Def: Conduct research in the genetics, nutrition, reproduction, growth, and development of domestic farm animals.

title: Food scientists & technologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Agricultural & food scientists/Food scientists & technologists
Def: Use chemistry, microbiology, engineering, and other sciences to study the principles underlying the processing and deterioration of foods; analyze food content to determine levels of vitamins, fat, sugar, and protein; discover new food sources; research ways to make processed foods safe, palatable, and healthful; and apply food science knowledge to determine best ways to process, package, preserve, store, and distribute food.

title: Soil & plant scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Agricultural & food scientists/Soil & plant scientists
Def: Conduct research in breeding, physiology, production, yield, and management of crops and agricultural plants or trees, shrubs, and nursery stock, their growth in soils, and control of pests; or study the chemical, physical, biological, and mineralogical composition of soils as they relate to plant or crop growth. May classify and map soils and investigate effects of alternative practices on soil and crop productivity.

title: Biological scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Biological scientists/Soil & plant scientists

title: Biochemists & biophysicists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Biological scientists/Biochemists & biophysicists
Def: Study the chemical composition or physical principles of living cells and organisms, their electrical and mechanical energy, and related phenomena. May conduct research to further understanding of the complex chemical combinations and reactions involved in metabolism, reproduction, growth, and heredity. May determine the effects of foods, drugs, serums, hormones, and other substances on tissues and vital processes of living organisms.

title: Microbiologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Biological scientists/Microbiologists
Def: Investigate the growth, structure, development, and other characteristics of microscopic organisms, such as bacteria, algae, or fungi. Includes medical microbiologists who study the relationship between organisms and disease or the effects of antibiotics on microorganisms.

title: Zoologists & wildlife biologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Biological scientists/Zoologists & wildlife biologists
Def: Study the origins, behavior, diseases, genetics, and life processes of animals and wildlife. May specialize in wildlife research and management. May collect and analyze biological data to determine the environmental effects of present and potential use of land and water habitats.

title: Biological scientists, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Biological scientists/Biological scientists, all other
Def: All biological scientists not listed separately.

title: Conservation scientists & foresters
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Conservation scientists & foresters/Biological scientists, all other

title: Conservation scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Conservation scientists & foresters/Conservation scientists
Def: Manage, improve, and protect natural resources to maximize their use without damaging the environment. May conduct soil surveys and develop plans to eliminate soil erosion or to protect rangelands. May instruct farmers, agricultural production managers, or ranchers in best ways to use crop rotation, contour plowing, or terracing to conserve soil and water; in the number and kind of livestock and forage plants best suited to particular ranges; and in range and farm improvements, such as fencing and reservoirs for stock watering. Excludes “Zoologists and Wildlife Biologists” (19-1023) and “Foresters” (19-1032).

title: Foresters
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Conservation scientists & foresters/Foresters
Def: Manage public and private forested lands for economic, recreational, and conservation purposes. May inventory the type, amount, and location of standing timber, appraise the timber’s worth, negotiate the purchase, and draw up contracts for procurement. May determine how to conserve wildlife habitats, creek beds, water quality, and soil stability, and how best to comply with environmental regulations. May devise plans for planting and growing new trees, monitor trees for healthy growth, and determine optimal harvesting schedules.

title: Medical scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Medical scientists/Foresters

title: Epidemiologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Medical scientists/Epidemiologists
Def: Investigate and describe the determinants and distribution of disease, disability, or health outcomes. May develop the means for prevention and control.

title: Medical scientists, except epidemiologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Medical scientists/Medical scientists, except epidemiologists
Def: Conduct research dealing with the understanding of human diseases and the improvement of human health. Engage in clinical investigation, research and development, or other related activities. Includes physicians, dentists, pharmacologists, and medical pathologists who primarily conduct research. Practitioners who primarily provide medical or dental care or dispense drugs are included in “Healthcare Diagnosing or Treating Practitioners” (29-1000).

title: Life scientists, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life scientists/Life scientists, all other/Medical scientists, except epidemiologists
Def: All life scientists not listed separately.

title: Physical scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Life scientists, all other/Medical scientists, except epidemiologists

title: Astronomers & physicists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Astronomers & physicists/Medical scientists, except epidemiologists

title: Astronomers
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Astronomers & physicists/Astronomers
Def: Observe, research, and interpret astronomical phenomena to increase basic knowledge or apply such information to practical problems.

title: Physicists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Astronomers & physicists/Physicists
Def: Conduct research into physical phenomena, develop theories on the basis of observation and experiments, and devise methods to apply physical laws and theories. Excludes “Biochemists and Biophysicists” (19-1021).

title: Atmospheric & space scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Atmospheric & space scientists/Physicists
Def: Investigate atmospheric phenomena and interpret meteorological data, gathered by surface and air stations, satellites, and radar to prepare reports and forecasts for public and other uses. Includes weather analysts and forecasters whose functions require the detailed knowledge of meteorology.

title: Chemists & materials scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Chemists & materials scientists/Physicists

title: Chemists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Chemists & materials scientists/Chemists
Def: Conduct qualitative and quantitative chemical analyses or experiments in laboratories for quality or process control or to develop new products or knowledge. Excludes “Biochemists and Biophysicists” (19-1021) and “Geoscientists, Except Hydrologists and Geographers” (19-2042).

title: Materials scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Chemists & materials scientists/Materials scientists
Def: Research and study the structures and chemical properties of various natural and synthetic or composite materials, including metals, alloys, rubber, ceramics, semiconductors, polymers, and glass. Determine ways to strengthen or combine materials or develop new materials with new or specific properties for use in a variety of products and applications. Includes glass scientists, ceramic scientists, metallurgical scientists, and polymer scientists.

title: Environmental scientists & geoscientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Environmental scientists & geoscientists/Materials scientists

title: Environmental scientists & specialists, including health
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Environmental scientists & geoscientists/Environmental scientists & specialists, including health
Def: Conduct research or perform investigation for the purpose of identifying, abating, or eliminating sources of pollutants or hazards that affect either the environment or public health. Using knowledge of various scientific disciplines, may collect, synthesize, study, report, and recommend action based on data derived from measurements or observations of air, food, soil, water, and other sources. Excludes “Zoologists and Wildlife Biologists” (19-1023), “Conservation Scientists” (19-1031), “Forest and Conservation Technicians” (19-4071), “Occupational Health and Safety Specialists” (19-5011), “Fish and Game Wardens” (33-3031), and “Forest and Conservation Workers” (45-4011).

title: Geoscientists, except hydrologists & geographers
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Environmental scientists & geoscientists/Geoscientists, except hydrologists & geographers
Def: Study the composition, structure, and other physical aspects of the Earth. May use geological, physics, and mathematics knowledge in exploration for oil, gas, minerals, or underground water; or in waste disposal, land reclamation, or other environmental problems. May study the Earth’s internal composition, atmospheres, and oceans, and its magnetic, electrical, and gravitational forces. Includes mineralogists, paleontologists, stratigraphers, geodesists, and seismologists.

title: Hydrologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Environmental scientists & geoscientists/Hydrologists
Def: Research the distribution, circulation, and physical properties of underground and surface waters; and study the form and intensity of precipitation and its rate of infiltration into the soil, movement through the earth, and return to the ocean and atmosphere.

title: Physical scientists, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Physical scientists/Physical scientists, all other/Hydrologists
Def: All physical scientists not listed separately.

title: Social scientists & related workers
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Physical scientists, all other/Hydrologists

title: Economists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Economists/Hydrologists
Def: Conduct research, prepare reports, or formulate plans to address economic problems related to the production and distribution of goods and services or monetary and fiscal policy. May collect and process economic and statistical data using sampling techniques and econometric methods. Excludes “Market Research Analysts and Marketing Specialists” (13-1161).

title: Survey researchers
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Survey researchers/Hydrologists
Def: Plan, develop, or conduct surveys. May analyze and interpret the meaning of survey data, determine survey objectives, or suggest or test question wording. Includes social scientists who primarily design questionnaires or supervise survey teams. Excludes “Market Research Analysts and Marketing Specialists” (13-1161) and “Statisticians” (15-2041).

title: Psychologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Psychologists/Hydrologists

title: Clinical, counseling, & school psychologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Psychologists/Clinical, counseling, etc

title: Industrial-organizational psychologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Psychologists/Industrial-organizational psychologists
Def: Apply principles of psychology to human resources, administration, management, sales, and marketing problems. Activities may include policy planning; employee testing and selection, training, and development; and organizational development and analysis. May work with management to organize the work setting to improve worker productivity.

title: Psychologists, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Psychologists/Psychologists, all other
Def: All psychologists not listed separately.

title: Sociologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Sociologists/Psychologists, all other
Def: Study human society and social behavior by examining the groups and social institutions that people form, as well as various social, religious, political, and business organizations. May study the behavior and interaction of groups, trace their origin and growth, and analyze the influence of group activities on individual members.

title: Urban & regional planners
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Urban & regional planners/Psychologists, all other
Def: Develop comprehensive plans and programs for use of land and physical facilities of jurisdictions, such as towns, cities, counties, and metropolitan areas.

title: Miscellaneous social scientists & related workers
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Miscellaneous social scientists & related workers/Psychologists, all other

title: Anthropologists & archeologists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Miscellaneous social scientists & related workers/Anthropologists & archeologists
Def: Study the origin, development, and behavior of human beings. May study the way of life, language, or physical characteristics of people in various parts of the world. May engage in systematic recovery and examination of material evidence, such as tools or pottery remaining from past human cultures, in order to determine the history, customs, and living habits of earlier civilizations.

title: Geographers
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Miscellaneous social scientists & related workers/Geographers
Def: Study the nature and use of areas of the Earth’s surface, relating and interpreting interactions of physical and cultural phenomena. Conduct research on physical aspects of a region, including land forms, climates, soils, plants, and animals, and conduct research on the spatial implications of human activities within a given area, including social characteristics, economic activities, and political organization, as well as researching interdependence between regions at scales ranging from local to global.

title: Historians
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Miscellaneous social scientists & related workers/Historians
Def: Research, analyze, record, and interpret the past as recorded in sources, such as government and institutional records, newspapers and other periodicals, photographs, interviews, films, electronic media, and unpublished manuscripts, such as personal diaries and letters.

title: Political scientists
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Miscellaneous social scientists & related workers/Political scientists
Def: Study the origin, development, and operation of political systems. May study topics, such as public opinion, political decisionmaking, and ideology. May analyze the structure and operation of governments, as well as various political entities. May conduct public opinion surveys, analyze election results, or analyze public documents. Excludes “Survey Researchers” (19-3022).

title: Social scientists & related workers, all other
ttl: Social scientists & related workers, all other
Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers/Miscellaneous social scientists & related workers/Social scientists & related workers, all other
Def: All social scientists and related workers not listed separately.

Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Miscellaneous social scientists & related workers/Social scientists & related workers, all other

title: Agricultural & food science technicians
Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Agricultural & food science technicians/Social scientists & related workers, all other

title: Biological technicians
Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Biological technicians/Social scientists & related workers, all other
Def: Assist biological and medical scientists. Set up, operate, and maintain laboratory instruments and equipment, monitor experiments, collect data and samples, make observations, and calculate and record results. May analyze organic substances, such as blood, food, and drugs.

title: Chemical technicians
Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Chemical technicians/Social scientists & related workers, all other
Def: Conduct chemical and physical laboratory tests to assist scientists in making qualitative and quantitative analyses of solids, liquids, and gaseous materials for research and development of new products or processes, quality control, maintenance of environmental standards, and other work involving experimental, theoretical, or practical application of chemistry and related sciences.

title: Geological & petroleum technicians
Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Geological & petroleum technicians/Social scientists & related workers, all other

title: Nuclear technicians
Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Nuclear technicians/Social scientists & related workers, all other
Def: Assist nuclear physicists, nuclear engineers, or other scientists in laboratory, power generation, or electricity production activities. May operate, maintain, or provide quality control for nuclear testing and research equipment. May monitor radiation.

title: Social science research assistants
Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Social science research assistants/Social scientists & related workers, all other
Def: Assist social scientists in laboratory, survey, and other social science research. May help prepare findings for publication and assist in laboratory analysis, quality control, or data management. Excludes “Teaching Assistants, Postsecondary” (25-9044).

title: Miscellaneous life, physical, & social science technicians
Level4: Social scientists & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Miscellaneous life, physical, etc/Social scientists & related workers, all other

title: Environmental science & protection technicians, including health
ttl: Environmental science & protection technicians, including health
Level4: Environmental science & protection technicians, including health
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Miscellaneous life, physical, etc/Environmental science & protection technicians, including health
Def: Perform laboratory and field tests to monitor the environment and investigate sources of pollution, including those that affect health, under the direction of an environmental scientist, engineer, or other specialist. May collect samples of gases, soil, water, and other materials for testing.

title: Forensic science technicians
pathString: Jobs/Life, physical, etc/Life, physical, etc/Miscellaneous life, physical, etc/Forensic science technicians
Def: Collect, identify, classify, and analyze physical evidence related to criminal investigations. Perform tests on weapons or substances, such as fiber, hair, and tissue to determine significance to investigation. May testify as expert witnesses on evidence or crime laboratory techniques. May serve as specialists in area of expertise, such as ballistics, fingerprinting, handwriting, or biochemistry.

title: Forest & conservation technicians

May work with specimens such as fossils, skeletal parts, or botanicals; or artifacts, textiles, or art. May identify and record objects or install and arrange them in exhibits. Includes book or document conservators.

pathString: Jobs/Education, training, etc/Librarians, curators, etc/Library technicians/Museum technicians & conservators
Def: Assist librarians by helping readers in the use of library catalogs, databases, and indexes to locate books and other materials; and by answering questions that require only brief consultation of standard reference. Compile records; sort and shelve books or other media; remove or repair damaged books or other media; register patrons; and check materials in and out of the circulation process. Replace materials in shelving area (stacks) or files. Includes bookmobile drivers who assist with providing services in mobile libraries.

title: Craft artists
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Art & design workers/Artists & related workers/Craft artists
Def: Create or reproduce handmade objects for sale and exhibition using a variety of techniques, such as welding, weaving, pottery, and needlecraft.

title: Commercial & industrial designers
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Art & design workers/Designers/Commercial & industrial designers
Def: Design and develop manufactured products, such as cars, home appliances, and children’s toys. Combine artistic talent with research on product use, marketing, and materials to create the most functional and appealing product design.

title: Fashion designers
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Art & design workers/Designers/Fashion designers
Def: Design clothing and accessories. Create original designs or adapt fashion trends.

title: Floral designers
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Art & design workers/Designers/Floral designers
Def: Design, cut, and arrange live, dried, or artificial flowers and foliage.

title: Graphic designers
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Art & design workers/Designers/Graphic designers
Def: Design or create graphics to meet specific commercial or promotional needs, such as packaging, displays, or logos. May use a variety of mediums to achieve artistic or decorative effects. Excludes “Web and Digital Interface Designers” (15-1255).

title: Interior designers
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Art & design workers/Designers/Interior designers
Def: Plan, design, and furnish the internal space of rooms or buildings. Design interior environments or create physical layouts that are practical, aesthetic, and conducive to the intended purposes. May specialize in a particular field, style, or phase of interior design. Excludes “Merchandise Displayers and Window Trimmers” (27-1026).

Def: Play parts in stage, television, radio, video, or film productions, or other settings for entertainment, information, or instruction. Interpret serious or comic role by speech, gesture, and body movement to entertain or inform audience. May dance and sing.

title: Producers & directors
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Entertainers & performers, sports & related workers/Actors, producers, etc/Producers & directors
Def: Produce or direct stage, television, radio, video, or film productions for entertainment, information, or instruction. Responsible for creative decisions, such as interpretation of script, choice of actors or guests, set design, sound, special effects, and choreography.

title: Coaches & scouts
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Entertainers & performers, sports & related workers/Athletes, coaches, etc/Coaches & scouts
Def: Instruct or coach groups or individuals in the fundamentals of sports for the primary purpose of competition. Demonstrate techniques and methods of participation. May evaluate athletes’ strengths and weaknesses as possible recruits or to improve the athletes’ technique to prepare them for competition. Those required to hold teaching certifications should be reported in the appropriate teaching category. Excludes “Athletic Trainers” (29-9091).

title: Umpires, referees, & other sports officials
pathString: Jobs/Arts, design, etc/Entertainers & performers, sports & related workers/Athletes, coaches, etc/Umpires, referees, etc
Def: Officiate at competitive athletic or sporting events. Detect infractions of rules and decide penalties according to established regulations. Includes all sporting officials, referees, and competition judges.

Def: Play one or more musical instruments or sing. May perform on stage, for broadcasting, or for sound or video recording.

Def: Write technical materials, such as equipment manuals, appendices, or operating and maintenance instructions. May assist in layout work.

title: Writers & authors

Def: Originate and prepare written material, such as scripts, stories, advertisements, and other material. Excludes “News Analysts, Reporters, and Journalists” (27-3023), “Public Relations Specialists” (27-3031), and “Technical Writers” (27-3042).
