title: Switchboard operators, including answering service
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Communications equipment operators/Switchboard operators, including answering service/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Operate telephone business systems equipment or switchboards to relay incoming, outgoing, and interoffice calls. May supply information to callers and record messages.

title: Telephone operators
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Communications equipment operators/Telephone operators/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Provide information by accessing alphabetical, geographical, or other directories. Assist customers with special billing requests, such as charges to a third party and credits or refunds for incorrectly dialed numbers or bad connections. May handle emergency calls and assist children or people with physical disabilities to make telephone calls.

title: Communications equipment operators, all other
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Communications equipment operators/Communications equipment operators, all other/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: All communications equipment operators not listed separately.

title: Financial clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Communications equipment operators, all other/Sales & related workers, all other

title: Bill & account collectors
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Bill & account collectors/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Locate and notify customers of delinquent accounts by mail, telephone, or personal visit to solicit payment. Duties include receiving payment and posting amount to customer’s account, preparing statements to credit department if customer fails to respond, initiating repossession proceedings or service disconnection, and keeping records of collection and status of accounts.

title: Billing & posting clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Billing & posting clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Compile, compute, and record billing, accounting, statistical, and other numerical data for billing purposes. Prepare billing invoices for services rendered or for delivery or shipment of goods. Excludes “Medical Records Specialists” (29-2072).

title: Bookkeeping, accounting, & auditing clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Bookkeeping, accounting, etc/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Compute, classify, and record numerical data to keep financial records complete. Perform any combination of routine calculating, posting, and verifying duties to obtain primary financial data for use in maintaining accounting records. May also check the accuracy of figures, calculations, and postings pertaining to business transactions recorded by other workers. Excludes “Payroll and Timekeeping Clerks” (43-3051).

title: Gaming cage workers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Gaming cage workers/Sales & related workers, all other

title: Payroll & timekeeping clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Payroll & timekeeping clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Compile and record employee time and payroll data. May compute employees’ time worked, production, and commission. May compute and post wages and deductions, or prepare paychecks. Excludes “Bookkeeping, Accounting, and Auditing Clerks” (43-3031).

title: Procurement clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Procurement clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Compile information and records to draw up purchase orders for procurement of materials and services. Excludes “Wholesale and Retail Buyers, Except Farm Products” (13-1022).

title: Tellers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Tellers/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Receive and pay out money. Keep records of money and negotiable instruments involved in a financial institution’s various transactions.

title: Financial clerks, all other
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Financial clerks/Financial clerks, all other/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: All financial clerks not listed separately.

title: Information & record clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Financial clerks, all other/Sales & related workers, all other

title: Brokerage clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Brokerage clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Perform duties related to the purchase, sale, or holding of securities. Duties include writing orders for stock purchases or sales, computing transfer taxes, verifying stock transactions, accepting and delivering securities, tracking stock price fluctuations, computing equity, distributing dividends, and keeping records of daily transactions and holdings.

title: Correspondence clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Correspondence clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Compose letters or electronic correspondence in reply to requests for merchandise, damage claims, credit and other information, delinquent accounts, incorrect billings, or unsatisfactory services. Duties may include gathering data to formulate reply and preparing correspondence.

title: Court, municipal, & license clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Court, municipal, etc/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Perform clerical duties for courts of law, municipalities, or governmental licensing agencies and bureaus. May prepare docket of cases to be called; secure information for judges and court; prepare draft agendas or bylaws for town or city council; answer official correspondence; keep fiscal records and accounts; issue licenses or permits; and record data, administer tests, or collect fees. Clerks of Court are classified in “Managers, All Other” (11-9199).

title: Credit authorizers, checkers, & clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Credit authorizers, checkers, etc/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Authorize credit charges against customers’ accounts. Investigate history and credit standing of individuals or business establishments applying for credit. May interview applicants to obtain personal and financial data, determine credit worthiness, process applications, and notify customers of acceptance or rejection of credit.

title: Customer service representatives
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Customer service representatives/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Interact with customers to provide basic or scripted information in response to routine inquiries about products and services. May handle and resolve general complaints. Excludes individuals whose duties are primarily installation, sales, repair, and technical support.

title: Eligibility interviewers, government programs
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Eligibility interviewers, government programs/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Determine eligibility of persons applying to receive assistance from government programs and agency resources, such as welfare, unemployment benefits, social security, and public housing.

title: File clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/File clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: File correspondence, cards, invoices, receipts, and other records in alphabetical or numerical order or according to the filing system used. Locate and remove material from file when requested.

title: Hotel, motel, & resort desk clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Hotel, motel, etc/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Accommodate hotel, motel, and resort patrons by registering and assigning rooms to guests, issuing room keys or cards, transmitting and receiving messages, keeping records of occupied rooms and guests’ accounts, making and confirming reservations, and presenting statements to and collecting payments from departing guests.

title: Interviewers, except eligibility & loan
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Interviewers, except eligibility & loan/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Interview persons by telephone, mail, in person, or by other means for the purpose of completing forms, applications, or questionnaires. Ask specific questions, record answers, and assist persons with completing form. May sort, classify, and file forms.

title: Library assistants, clerical
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Library assistants, clerical/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Compile records, and sort, shelve, issue, and receive library materials such as books, electronic media, pictures, cards, slides and microfilm. Locate library materials for loan and replace material in shelving area, stacks, or files according to identification number and title. Register patrons to permit them to borrow books, periodicals, and other library materials. Excludes “Library Technicians” (25-4031).

title: Loan interviewers & clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Loan interviewers & clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Interview loan applicants to elicit information; investigate applicants’ backgrounds and verify references; prepare loan request papers; and forward findings, reports, and documents to appraisal department. Review loan papers to ensure completeness, and complete transactions between loan establishment, borrowers, and sellers upon approval of loan.

title: New accounts clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/New accounts clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Interview persons desiring to open accounts in financial institutions. Explain account services available to prospective customers and assist them in preparing applications.

title: Order clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Order clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Receive and process incoming orders for materials, merchandise, classified ads, or services such as repairs, installations, or rental of facilities. Generally receives orders via mail, phone, fax, or other electronic means. Duties include informing customers of receipt, prices, shipping dates, and delays; preparing contracts; and handling complaints. Excludes “Dispatchers, Except Police, Fire, and Ambulance” (43-5032) who both dispatch and take orders for services.

title: Human resources assistants, except payroll & timekeeping
ttl: Human resources assistants, except payroll & timekeeping
Level3: Human resources assistants, except payroll & timekeeping
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Human resources assistants, except payroll & timekeeping/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Compile and keep personnel records. Record data for each employee, such as address, weekly earnings, absences, amount of sales or production, supervisory reports, and date of and reason for termination. May prepare reports for employment records, file employment records, or search employee files and furnish information to authorized persons.

title: Receptionists & information clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Receptionists & information clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Answer inquiries and provide information to the general public, customers, visitors, and other interested parties regarding activities conducted at establishment and location of departments, offices, and employees within the organization. Excludes “Switchboard Operators, Including Answering Service” (43-2011).

title: Reservation & transportation ticket agents & travel clerks
ttl: Reservation & transportation ticket agents & travel clerks
Level3: Reservation & transportation ticket agents & travel clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Reservation & transportation ticket agents & travel clerks/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Make and confirm reservations for transportation or lodging, or sell transportation tickets. May check baggage and direct passengers to designated concourse, pier, or track; deliver tickets and contact individuals and groups to inform them of package tours; or provide tourists with travel or transportation information. Excludes "Cashiers” (41-2011), "Travel Agents” (41-3041), and "Hotel, Motel, and Resort Desk Clerks” (43-4081) who sell tickets for local transportation.

title: Information & record clerks, all other
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Information & record clerks/Information & record clerks, all other/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: All information and record clerks not listed separately.

title: Material recording, scheduling, dispatching, & distributing workers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Information & record clerks, all other/Sales & related workers, all other

title: Cargo & freight agents
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Cargo & freight agents/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Expedite and route movement of incoming and outgoing cargo and freight shipments in airline, train, and trucking terminals and shipping docks. Take orders from customers and arrange pickup of freight and cargo for delivery to loading platform. Prepare and examine bills of lading to determine shipping charges and tariffs.

title: Couriers & messengers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Couriers & messengers/Sales & related workers, all other
Def: Pick up and deliver messages, documents, packages, and other items between offices or departments within an establishment or directly to other business concerns, traveling by foot, bicycle, motorcycle, automobile, or public conveyance. Excludes “Light Truck Drivers” (53-3033).

title: Dispatchers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Dispatchers/Sales & related workers, all other

title: Police, fire, & ambulance dispatchers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Dispatchers/Police, fire, etc

title: Dispatchers, except police, fire, & ambulance
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Dispatchers/Dispatchers, except police, etc
Def: Schedule and dispatch workers, work crews, equipment, or service vehicles for conveyance of materials, freight, or passengers, or for normal installation, service, or emergency repairs rendered outside the place of business. Duties may include using radio, telephone, or computer to transmit assignments and compiling statistics and reports on work progress.

title: Meter readers, utilities
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Meter readers, utilities/Dispatchers, except police, etc
Def: Read meter and record consumption of electricity, gas, water, or steam.

title: Postal service workers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Postal service workers/Dispatchers, except police, etc

title: Postal service clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Postal service workers/Postal service clerks
Def: Perform any combination of tasks in a United States Postal Service (USPS) post office, such as receive letters and parcels; sell postage and revenue stamps, postal cards, and stamped envelopes; fill out and sell money orders; place mail in pigeon holes of mail rack or in bags; and examine mail for correct postage. Includes postal service clerks employed by USPS contractors.

title: Postal service mail carriers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Postal service workers/Postal service mail carriers
Def: Sort and deliver mail for the United States Postal Service (USPS). Deliver mail on established route by vehicle or on foot. Includes postal service mail carriers employed by USPS contractors.

title: Postal service mail sorters, processors, & processing machine operators
ttl: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Postal service workers/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
Def: Prepare incoming and outgoing mail for distribution for the United States Postal Service (USPS). Examine, sort, and route mail. Load, operate, and occasionally adjust and repair mail processing, sorting, and canceling machinery. Keep records of shipments, pouches, and sacks, and perform other duties related to mail handling within the postal service. Includes postal service mail sorters and processors employed by USPS contractors. Excludes “Postal Service Clerks” (43-5051) and “Postal Service Mail Carriers” (43-5052).

title: Production, planning, & expediting clerks
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Production, planning, etc/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
Def: Coordinate and expedite the flow of work and materials within or between departments of an establishment according to production schedule. Duties include reviewing and distributing production, work, and shipment schedules; conferring with department supervisors to determine progress of work and completion dates; and compiling reports on progress of work, inventory levels, costs, and production problems. Excludes “Project Management Specialists” (13-1082) and “Weighers, Measurers, Checkers, and Samplers, Recordkeeping” (43-5111).

title: Shipping, receiving, & traffic clerks
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Shipping, receiving, etc/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc

title: Stock clerks & order fillers
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Stock clerks & order fillers/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc

title: Weighers, measurers, checkers, & samplers, recordkeeping
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Material recording, scheduling, etc/Weighers, measurers, etc/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
Def: Weigh, measure, and check materials, supplies, and equipment for the purpose of keeping relevant records. Duties are primarily clerical by nature. Includes workers who collect and keep record of samples of products or materials. Excludes “Inspectors, Testers, Sorters, Samplers, and Weighers” (51-9061).

title: Secretaries & administrative assistants
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Secretaries & administrative assistants/Weighers, measurers, etc/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc

title: Executive secretaries & executive administrative assistants
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Secretaries & administrative assistants/Executive secretaries & executive administrative assistants/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
Def: Provide high-level administrative support by conducting research, preparing statistical reports, and handling information requests, as well as performing routine administrative functions such as preparing correspondence, receiving visitors, arranging conference calls, and scheduling meetings. May also train and supervise lower-level clerical staff. Excludes “Secretaries” (43-6012 through 43-6014).

title: Legal secretaries
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Secretaries & administrative assistants/Legal secretaries/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc

title: Medical secretaries
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Secretaries & administrative assistants/Medical secretaries/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc

title: Secretaries & administrative assistants, except legal, medical, & executive
ttl: Secretaries & administrative assistants, except legal, etc
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
Level3: Secretaries & administrative assistants, except legal, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Secretaries & administrative assistants/Secretaries & administrative assistants, except legal, etc/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
Def: Perform routine administrative functions such as drafting correspondence, scheduling appointments, organizing and maintaining paper and electronic files, or providing information to callers. Excludes legal, medical, and executive secretaries (43-6011 through 43-6013).

title: Other office & administrative support workers
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
Level3: Secretaries & administrative assistants, except legal, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Secretaries & administrative assistants, except legal, etc/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc

title: Computer operators
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Computer operators/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc

title: Data entry & information processing workers
Level4: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Data entry & information processing workers/Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc

title: Data entry keyers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Data entry & information processing workers/Data entry keyers
Def: Operate data entry device, such as keyboard or photo composing perforator. Duties may include verifying data and preparing materials for printing. Excludes “Word Processors and Typists” (43-9022).

title: Word processors & typists
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Data entry & information processing workers/Word processors & typists
Def: Use word processor, computer, or typewriter to type letters, reports, forms, or other material from rough draft, corrected copy, or voice recording. May perform other clerical duties as assigned. Excludes “Court Reporters and Simultaneous Captioners” (27-3092), “Medical Transcriptionists” (31-9094), “Secretaries and Administrative Assistants” (43-6010), and “Data Entry Keyers” (43-9021).

title: Desktop publishers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Desktop publishers/Word processors & typists
Def: Format typescript and graphic elements using computer software to produce publication-ready material.

title: Insurance claims & policy processing clerks
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Insurance claims & policy processing clerks/Word processors & typists
Def: Process new insurance policies, modifications to existing policies, and claims forms. Obtain information from policyholders to verify the accuracy and completeness of information on claims forms, applications and related documents, and company records. Update existing policies and company records to reflect changes requested by policyholders and insurance company representatives. Excludes “Claims Adjusters, Examiners, and Investigators” (13-1031).

title: Mail clerks & mail machine operators, except postal service
ttl: Mail clerks & mail machine operators, except postal service
Level3: Mail clerks & mail machine operators, except postal service
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Mail clerks & mail machine operators, except postal service/Word processors & typists
Def: Prepare incoming and outgoing mail for distribution. Time-stamp, open, read, sort, and route incoming mail; and address, seal, stamp, fold, stuff, and affix postage to outgoing mail or packages. Duties may also include keeping necessary records and completed forms.

title: Office clerks, general
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Office clerks, general/Word processors & typists
Def: Perform duties too varied and diverse to be classified in any specific office clerical occupation, requiring knowledge of office systems and procedures. Clerical duties may be assigned in accordance with the office procedures of individual establishments and may include a combination of answering telephones, bookkeeping, typing or word processing, office machine operation, and filing.

title: Office machine operators, except computer
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Office machine operators, except computer/Word processors & typists
Def: Operate one or more of a variety of office machines, such as photocopying, photographic, and duplicating machines, or other office machines. Excludes “Billing and Posting Clerks” (43-3021) and “Mail Clerks and Mail Machine Operators, Except Postal Service” (43-9051).

title: Proofreaders & copy markers
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Proofreaders & copy markers/Word processors & typists
Def: Read transcript or proof type setup to detect and mark for correction any grammatical, typographical, or compositional errors. Excludes workers whose primary duty is editing copy. Includes proofreaders of braille.

title: Statistical assistants
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Statistical assistants/Word processors & typists
Def: Compile and compute data according to statistical formulas for use in statistical studies. May perform actuarial computations and compile charts and graphs for use by actuaries. Includes actuarial clerks.

title: Office & administrative support workers, all other
ttl: Office & administrative support workers, all other
Level3: Office & administrative support workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Office & administrative support occupations/Other office & administrative support workers/Office & administrative support workers, all other/Word processors & typists
Def: All office and administrative support workers not listed separately.

title: Farming, fishing, & forestry occupations
Level3: Office & administrative support workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Other office & administrative support workers/Office & administrative support workers, all other/Word processors & typists

title: Supervisors of farming, fishing, & forestry workers
Level3: Office & administrative support workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Supervisors of farming, fishing, etc/Office & administrative support workers, all other/Word processors & typists

title: First-line supervisors of farming, fishing, & forestry workers
ttl: First-line supervisors of farming, fishing, etc
Level3: First-line supervisors of farming, fishing, etc
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Supervisors of farming, fishing, etc/First-line supervisors of farming, fishing, etc/Word processors & typists
Def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of agricultural, forestry, aquacultural, and related workers. Excludes “First-Line Supervisors of Landscaping, Lawn Service, and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-1012).

title: Agricultural workers
Level3: First-line supervisors of farming, fishing, etc
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/First-line supervisors of farming, fishing, etc/Word processors & typists

title: Agricultural inspectors
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/Agricultural inspectors/Word processors & typists
Def: Inspect agricultural commodities, processing equipment, and facilities, and fish and logging operations, to ensure compliance with regulations and laws governing health, quality, and safety.

title: Animal breeders
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/Animal breeders/Word processors & typists
Def: Select and breed animals according to their genealogy, characteristics, and offspring. May require knowledge of artificial insemination techniques and equipment use. May involve keeping records on heats, birth intervals, or pedigree. Excludes “Animal Scientists” (19-1011) whose primary function is research and “Animal Caretakers” (39-2021) who may occasionally breed animals as part of their other caretaking duties.

title: Graders & sorters, agricultural products
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/Graders & sorters, agricultural products/Word processors & typists
Def: Grade, sort, or classify unprocessed food and other agricultural products by size, weight, color, or condition. Excludes “Agricultural Inspectors” (45-2011).

title: Miscellaneous agricultural workers
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/Miscellaneous agricultural workers/Word processors & typists

title: Agricultural equipment operators
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/Miscellaneous agricultural workers/Agricultural equipment operators
Def: Drive and control equipment to support agricultural activities such as tilling soil; planting, cultivating, and harvesting crops; feeding and herding livestock; or removing animal waste. May perform tasks such as crop baling or hay bucking. May operate stationary equipment to perform post-harvest tasks such as husking, shelling, threshing, and ginning.

title: Farmworkers & laborers, crop, nursery, & greenhouse
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/Miscellaneous agricultural workers/Farmworkers & laborers, crop, etc
Def: Manually plant, cultivate, and harvest vegetables, fruits, nuts, horticultural specialties, and field crops. Use hand tools, such as shovels, trowels, hoes, tampers, pruning hooks, shears, and knives. Duties may include tilling soil and applying fertilizers; transplanting, weeding, thinning, or pruning crops; applying pesticides; or cleaning, grading, sorting, packing, and loading harvested products. May construct trellises, repair fences and farm buildings, or participate in irrigation activities. Excludes “Pesticide Handlers, Sprayers, and Applicators, Vegetation” (37-3012), “Graders and Sorters, Agricultural Products” (45-2041), and “Forest, Conservation, and Logging Workers” (45-4011 through 45-4029).

title: Farmworkers, farm, ranch, & aquacultural animals
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/Miscellaneous agricultural workers/Farmworkers, farm, etc
Def: Attend to live farm, ranch, open range or aquacultural animals that may include cattle, sheep, swine, goats, horses and other equines, poultry, rabbits, finfish, shellfish, and bees. Attend to animals produced for animal products, such as meat, fur, skins, feathers, eggs, milk, and honey. Duties may include feeding, watering, herding, grazing, milking, castrating, branding, de-beaking, weighing, catching, and loading animals. May maintain records on animals; examine animals to detect diseases and injuries; assist in birth deliveries; and administer medications, vaccinations, or insecticides as appropriate. May clean and maintain animal housing areas. Includes workers who shear wool from sheep and collect eggs in hatcheries.

title: Agricultural workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Agricultural workers/Miscellaneous agricultural workers/Agricultural workers, all other
Def: All agricultural workers not listed separately.

title: Fishing & hunting workers
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Fishing & hunting workers/Miscellaneous agricultural workers/Agricultural workers, all other
Def: Hunt, trap, catch, or gather wild animals or aquatic animals and plants. May use nets, traps, or other equipment. May haul catch onto ship or other vessel. Aquacultural laborers who work on fish farms are included in “Farmworkers, Farm, Ranch, and Aquacultural Animals” (45-2093).

title: Forest, conservation, & logging workers
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Forest, conservation, etc/Miscellaneous agricultural workers/Agricultural workers, all other

title: Forest & conservation workers
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Forest, conservation, etc/Forest & conservation workers/Agricultural workers, all other
Def: Under supervision, perform manual labor necessary to develop, maintain, or protect areas such as forests, forested areas, woodlands, wetlands, and rangelands through such activities as raising and transporting seedlings; combating insects, pests, and diseases harmful to plant life; and building structures to control water, erosion, and leaching of soil. Includes forester aides, seedling pullers, tree planters, and gatherers of nontimber forestry products such as pine straw.

title: Logging workers
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Forest, conservation, etc/Logging workers/Agricultural workers, all other

title: Fallers
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Forest, conservation, etc/Logging workers/Fallers
Def: Use axes or chainsaws to fell trees using knowledge of tree characteristics and cutting techniques to control direction of fall and minimize tree damage.

title: Logging equipment operators
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Forest, conservation, etc/Logging workers/Logging equipment operators
Def: Drive logging tractor or wheeled vehicle equipped with one or more accessories, such as bulldozer blade, frontal shear, grapple, logging arch, cable winches, hoisting rack, or crane boom, to fell tree; to skid, load, unload, or stack logs; or to pull stumps or clear brush. Includes operating stand-alone logging machines, such as log chippers. Logging truck drivers are included in “Heavy and Tractor-Trailer Truck Drivers” (53-3032).

title: Log graders & scalers
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Forest, conservation, etc/Logging workers/Log graders & scalers
Def: Grade logs or estimate the marketable content or value of logs or pulpwood in sorting yards, millpond, log deck, or similar locations. Inspect logs for defects or measure logs to determine volume. Excludes “Buyers and Purchasing Agents, Farm Products” (13-1021).

title: Logging workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Farming, fishing, etc/Forest, conservation, etc/Logging workers/Logging workers, all other
Def: All logging workers not listed separately.

title: Construction & extraction occupations
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Forest, conservation, etc/Logging workers/Logging workers, all other

title: Supervisors of construction & extraction workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Supervisors of construction & extraction workers/Logging workers/Logging workers, all other

ttl: First-line supervisors of construction trades & extraction workers
Level3: First-line supervisors of construction trades & extraction workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Supervisors of construction & extraction workers/First-line supervisors of construction trades & extraction workers/Logging workers, all other
Def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of construction or extraction workers.

title: Construction trades workers
Level3: First-line supervisors of construction trades & extraction workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/First-line supervisors of construction trades & extraction workers/Logging workers, all other

title: Boilermakers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Boilermakers/Logging workers, all other
Def: Construct, assemble, maintain, and repair stationary steam boilers and boiler house auxiliaries. Align structures or plate sections to assemble boiler frame tanks or vats, following blueprints. Work involves use of hand and power tools, plumb bobs, levels, wedges, dogs, or turnbuckles. Assist in testing assembled vessels. Direct cleaning of boilers and boiler furnaces. Inspect and repair boiler fittings, such as safety valves, regulators, automatic-control mechanisms, water columns, and auxiliary machines.

title: Brickmasons, blockmasons, & stonemasons
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Brickmasons, blockmasons, etc/Logging workers, all other

title: Brickmasons & blockmasons
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Brickmasons, blockmasons, etc/Brickmasons & blockmasons
Def: Lay and bind building materials, such as brick, structural tile, concrete block, cinder block, glass block, and terra-cotta block, with mortar and other substances, to construct or repair walls, partitions, arches, sewers, and other structures. Installers of mortarless segmental concrete masonry wall units are classified in “Landscaping and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-3011). Excludes “Stonemasons” (47-2022).

title: Stonemasons
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Brickmasons, blockmasons, etc/Stonemasons
Def: Build stone structures, such as piers, walls, and abutments. Lay walks, curbstones, or special types of masonry for vats, tanks, and floors.

title: Carpenters
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Carpenters/Stonemasons
Def: Construct, erect, install, or repair structures and fixtures made of wood and comparable materials, such as concrete forms; building frameworks, including partitions, joists, studding, and rafters; and wood stairways, window and door frames, and hardwood floors. May also install cabinets, siding, drywall, and batt or roll insulation. Includes brattice builders who build doors or brattices (ventilation walls or partitions) in underground passageways.

title: Carpet, floor, & tile installers & finishers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Carpet, floor, etc/Stonemasons

title: Carpet installers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Carpet, floor, etc/Carpet installers
Def: Lay and install carpet from rolls or blocks on floors. Install padding and trim flooring materials. Excludes “Floor Layers, Except Carpet, Wood, and Hard Tiles” (47-2042).

title: Floor layers, except carpet, wood, & hard tiles
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Carpet, floor, etc/Floor layers, except carpet, etc
Def: Apply blocks, strips, or sheets of shock-absorbing, sound-deadening, or decorative coverings to floors.

title: Floor sanders & finishers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Carpet, floor, etc/Floor sanders & finishers

title: Tile & marble setters
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Carpet, floor, etc/Tile & marble setters

title: Cement masons, concrete finishers, & terrazzo workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Cement masons, concrete finishers, etc/Tile & marble setters

title: Cement masons & concrete finishers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Cement masons, concrete finishers, etc/Cement masons & concrete finishers
Def: Smooth and finish surfaces of poured concrete, such as floors, walks, sidewalks, roads, or curbs using a variety of hand and power tools. Align forms for sidewalks, curbs, or gutters; patch voids; and use saws to cut expansion joints. Installers of mortarless segmental concrete masonry wall units are classified in “Landscaping and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-3011).

title: Terrazzo workers & finishers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Cement masons, concrete finishers, etc/Terrazzo workers & finishers
Def: Apply a mixture of cement, sand, pigment, or marble chips to floors, stairways, and cabinet fixtures to fashion durable and decorative surfaces.

title: Construction laborers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Construction laborers/Terrazzo workers & finishers
Def: Perform tasks involving physical labor at construction sites. May operate hand and power tools of all types: air hammers, earth tampers, cement mixers, small mechanical hoists, surveying and measuring equipment, and a variety of other equipment and instruments. May clean and prepare sites, dig trenches, set braces to support the sides of excavations, erect scaffolding, and clean up rubble, debris, and other waste materials. May assist other craft workers. Construction laborers who primarily assist a particular craft worker are classified under “Helpers, Construction Trades” (47-3010). Excludes “Hazardous Materials Removal Workers” (47-4041).

title: Construction equipment operators
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Construction equipment operators/Terrazzo workers & finishers

title: Paving, surfacing, & tamping equipment operators
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Construction equipment operators/Paving, surfacing, etc
Def: Operate equipment used for applying concrete, asphalt, or other materials to road beds, parking lots, or airport runways and taxiways or for tamping gravel, dirt, or other materials. Includes concrete and asphalt paving machine operators, form tampers, tamping machine operators, and stone spreader operators.

title: Pile-driver operators
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Construction equipment operators/Pile-driver operators

title: Operating engineers & other construction equipment operators
ttl: Operating engineers & other construction equipment operators
Level4: Operating engineers & other construction equipment operators
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Construction equipment operators/Operating engineers & other construction equipment operators
Def: Operate one or several types of power construction equipment, such as motor graders, bulldozers, scrapers, compressors, pumps, derricks, shovels, tractors, or front-end loaders to excavate, move, and grade earth, erect structures, or pour concrete or other hard surface pavement. May repair and maintain equipment in addition to other duties. Excludes “Extraction Workers” (47-5000) and “Crane and Tower Operators” (53-7021).

title: Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, & tapers
ttl: Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc
Level4: Operating engineers & other construction equipment operators
Level3: Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc/Operating engineers & other construction equipment operators

title: Drywall & ceiling tile installers
Level3: Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc/Drywall & ceiling tile installers
Def: Apply plasterboard or other wallboard to ceilings or interior walls of buildings. Apply or mount acoustical tiles or blocks, strips, or sheets of shock-absorbing materials to ceilings and walls of buildings to reduce or reflect sound. Materials may be of decorative quality. Includes lathers who fasten wooden, metal, or rockboard lath to walls, ceilings, or partitions of buildings to provide support base for plaster, fireproofing, or acoustical material. Excludes “Carpenters” (47-2031), “Carpet Installers” (47-2041), and “Tile and Stone Setters” (47-2044).

title: Tapers
Level3: Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc/Tapers
Def: Seal joints between plasterboard or other wallboard to prepare wall surface for painting or papering.

title: Electricians
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Electricians/Tapers
Def: Install, maintain, and repair electrical wiring, equipment, and fixtures. Ensure that work is in accordance with relevant codes. May install or service street lights, intercom systems, or electrical control systems. Excludes “Security and Fire Alarm Systems Installers” (49-2098).

title: Glaziers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Glaziers/Tapers
Def: Install glass in windows, skylights, store fronts, and display cases, or on surfaces, such as building fronts, interior walls, ceilings, and tabletops.

title: Insulation workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Insulation workers/Tapers

title: Insulation workers, floor, ceiling, & wall
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Insulation workers/Insulation workers, floor, etc
Def: Line and cover structures with insulating materials. May work with batt, roll, or blown insulation materials.

title: Insulation workers, mechanical
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Insulation workers/Insulation workers, mechanical
Def: Apply insulating materials to pipes or ductwork, or other mechanical systems in order to help control and maintain temperature.

title: Painters & paperhangers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Painters & paperhangers/Insulation workers, mechanical

title: Painters, construction & maintenance
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Painters & paperhangers/Painters, construction & maintenance
Def: Paint walls, equipment, buildings, bridges, and other structural surfaces, using brushes, rollers, and spray guns. May remove old paint to prepare surface prior to painting. May mix colors or oils to obtain desired color or consistency. Excludes “Paperhangers” (47-2142).

title: Paperhangers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Painters & paperhangers/Paperhangers
Def: Cover interior walls or ceilings of rooms with decorative wallpaper or fabric, or attach advertising posters on surfaces such as walls and billboards. May remove old materials or prepare surfaces to be papered.

title: Pipelayers, plumbers, pipefitters, & steamfitters
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Pipelayers, plumbers, etc/Paperhangers

title: Pipelayers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Pipelayers, plumbers, etc/Pipelayers
Def: Lay pipe for storm or sanitation sewers, drains, and water mains. Perform any combination of the following tasks: grade trenches or culverts, position pipe, or seal joints. Excludes “Welders, Cutters, Solderers, and Brazers” (51-4121).

title: Plumbers, pipefitters, & steamfitters
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Pipelayers, plumbers, etc/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Assemble, install, alter, and repair pipelines or pipe systems that carry water, steam, air, or other liquids or gases. May install heating and cooling equipment and mechanical control systems. Includes sprinkler fitters.

title: Plasterers & stucco masons
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Plasterers & stucco masons/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Apply interior or exterior plaster, cement, stucco, or similar materials. May also set ornamental plaster.

title: Reinforcing iron & rebar workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Reinforcing iron & rebar workers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Position and secure steel bars or mesh in concrete forms in order to reinforce concrete. Use a variety of fasteners, rod-bending machines, blowtorches, and hand tools. Includes rod busters.

title: Roofers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Roofers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Cover roofs of structures with shingles, slate, asphalt, aluminum, wood, or related materials. May spray roofs, sidings, and walls with material to bind, seal, insulate, or soundproof sections of structures.

title: Sheet metal workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Sheet metal workers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Fabricate, assemble, install, and repair sheet metal products and equipment, such as ducts, control boxes, drainpipes, and furnace casings. Work may involve any of the following: setting up and operating fabricating machines to cut, bend, and straighten sheet metal; shaping metal over anvils, blocks, or forms using hammer; operating soldering and welding equipment to join sheet metal parts; or inspecting, assembling, and smoothing seams and joints of burred surfaces. Includes sheet metal duct installers who install prefabricated sheet metal ducts used for heating, air conditioning, or other purposes.

title: Structural iron & steel workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Structural iron & steel workers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Raise, place, and unite iron or steel girders, columns, and other structural members to form completed structures or structural frameworks. May erect metal storage tanks and assemble prefabricated metal buildings. Excludes “Reinforcing Iron and Rebar Workers” (47-2171).

title: Solar photovoltaic installers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Construction trades workers/Solar photovoltaic installers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Assemble, install, or maintain solar photovoltaic (PV) systems on roofs or other structures in compliance with site assessment and schematics. May include measuring, cutting, assembling, and bolting structural framing and solar modules. May perform minor electrical work such as current checks. Excludes solar PV electricians who are included in “Electricians” (47-2111) and solar thermal installers who are included in “Plumbers, Pipefitters, and Steamfitters” (47-2152).

title: Helpers, construction trades
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Helpers, construction trades/Solar photovoltaic installers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc

title: Helpers--brickmasons, blockmasons, stonemasons, & tile & marble setters
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Helpers, construction trades/Helpers--brickmasons, blockmasons, etc/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Help brickmasons, blockmasons, stonemasons, or tile and marble setters by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist brickmasons, blockmasons, and stonemasons or tile and marble setters are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--carpenters
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Helpers, construction trades/Helpers--carpenters/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Help carpenters by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist carpenters are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--electricians
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Helpers, construction trades/Helpers--electricians/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Help electricians by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist electricians are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--painters, paperhangers, plasterers, & stucco masons
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Helpers, construction trades/Helpers--painters, paperhangers, etc/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Help painters, paperhangers, plasterers, or stucco masons by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist painters, paperhangers, plasterers, or stucco masons are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--pipelayers, plumbers, pipefitters, & steamfitters
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Helpers, construction trades/Helpers--pipelayers, plumbers, etc/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Help plumbers, pipefitters, steamfitters, or pipelayers by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist plumbers, pipefitters, steamfitters, or pipelayers are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers--roofers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Helpers, construction trades/Helpers--roofers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Help roofers by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist roofers are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Helpers, construction trades, all other
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Helpers, construction trades/Helpers, construction trades, etc/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: All construction trades helpers not listed separately.

title: Other construction & related workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Helpers, construction trades, etc/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc

title: Construction & building inspectors
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Construction & building inspectors/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Inspect structures using engineering skills to determine structural soundness and compliance with specifications, building codes, and other regulations. Inspections may be general in nature or may be limited to a specific area, such as electrical systems or plumbing.

title: Elevator installers & repairers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Elevator installers & repairers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc

title: Fence erectors
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Fence erectors/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Erect and repair fences and fence gates, using hand and power tools.

title: Hazardous materials removal workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Hazardous materials removal workers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Identify, remove, pack, transport, or dispose of hazardous materials, including asbestos, lead-based paint, waste oil, fuel, transmission fluid, radioactive materials, or contaminated soil. Specialized training and certification in hazardous materials handling or a confined entry permit are generally required. May operate earth-moving equipment or trucks.

title: Highway maintenance workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Highway maintenance workers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Maintain highways, municipal and rural roads, airport runways, and rights-of-way. Duties include patching broken or eroded pavement and repairing guard rails, highway markers, and snow fences. May also mow or clear brush from along road, or plow snow from roadway. Excludes “Tree Trimmers and Pruners” (37-3013).

title: Rail-track laying & maintenance equipment operators
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Rail-track laying & maintenance equipment operators/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Lay, repair, and maintain track for standard or narrow-gauge railroad equipment used in regular railroad service or in plant yards, quarries, sand and gravel pits, and mines. Includes ballast cleaning machine operators and railroad bed tamping machine operators.

title: Septic tank servicers & sewer pipe cleaners
ttl: Septic tank servicers & sewer pipe cleaners
Level3: Septic tank servicers & sewer pipe cleaners
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Septic tank servicers & sewer pipe cleaners/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
Def: Clean and repair septic tanks, sewer lines, or drains. May patch walls and partitions of tank, replace damaged drain tile, or repair breaks in underground piping.

title: Miscellaneous construction & related workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Miscellaneous construction & related workers/Plumbers, pipefitters, etc

title: Segmental pavers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Miscellaneous construction & related workers/Segmental pavers
Def: Lay out, cut, and place segmental paving units. Includes installers of bedding and restraining materials for the paving units.

title: Construction & related workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Other construction & related workers/Miscellaneous construction & related workers/Construction & related workers, all other
Def: All construction and related workers not listed separately.

pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Derrick, rotary drill, etc/Construction & related workers, all other

title: Derrick operators, oil & gas
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Derrick, rotary drill, etc/Derrick operators, oil & gas
Def: Rig derrick equipment and operate pumps to circulate mud or fluid through drill hole.

title: Rotary drill operators, oil & gas
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Derrick, rotary drill, etc/Rotary drill operators, oil & gas
Def: Set up or operate a variety of drills to remove underground oil and gas, or remove core samples for testing during oil and gas exploration. Excludes “Earth Drillers, Except Oil and Gas” (47-5023).

title: Service unit operators, oil, gas, & mining
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Derrick, rotary drill, etc/Service unit operators, oil, etc

title: Earth drillers, except oil & gas
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Earth drillers, except oil & gas/Service unit operators, oil, etc
Def: Operate a variety of drills such as rotary, churn, and pneumatic to tap subsurface water and salt deposits, to remove core samples during mineral exploration or soil testing, and to facilitate the use of explosives in mining or construction. Includes horizontal and earth boring machine operators.

title: Explosives workers, ordnance handling experts, & blasters
ttl: Explosives workers, ordnance handling experts, etc
Level3: Explosives workers, ordnance handling experts, etc
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Explosives workers, ordnance handling experts, etc/Service unit operators, oil, etc

pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Mining machine operators/Service unit operators, oil, etc

title: Continuous mining machine operators
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Mining machine operators/Continuous mining machine operators
Def: Operate self-propelled mining machines that rip coal, metal and nonmetal ores, rock, stone, or sand from the mine face and load it onto conveyors, shuttle cars, or trucks in a continuous operation.

title: Mine cutting & channeling machine operators
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Mining machine operators/Mine cutting & channeling machine operators

title: Mining machine operators, all other
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Mining machine operators/Mining machine operators, all other

title: Rock splitters, quarry
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Rock splitters, quarry/Mining machine operators, all other
Def: Separate blocks of rough dimension stone from quarry mass using jackhammers, wedges, or chop saws.

title: Roof bolters, mining
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Roof bolters, mining/Mining machine operators, all other
Def: Operate machinery to install roof support bolts in underground mine.

title: Roustabouts, oil & gas
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Roustabouts, oil & gas/Mining machine operators, all other
Def: Assemble or repair oil field equipment using hand and power tools. Perform other tasks as needed.

title: Helpers--extraction workers
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Helpers--extraction workers/Mining machine operators, all other
Def: Help extraction craft workers, such as earth drillers, blasters and explosives workers, derrick operators, and mining machine operators, by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include supplying equipment or cleaning work area. Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

title: Extraction workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Construction & extraction occupations/Extraction workers/Extraction workers, all other/Mining machine operators, all other
Def: All extraction workers not listed separately.

title: Installation, maintenance, & repair occupations
pathString: Jobs/Installation, maintenance, etc/Extraction workers/Extraction workers, all other/Mining machine operators, all other

title: Supervisors of installation, maintenance, & repair workers
pathString: Jobs/Installation, maintenance, etc/Supervisors of installation, maintenance, etc/Extraction workers, all other/Mining machine operators, all other

ttl: First-line supervisors of mechanics, installers, etc
Level3: First-line supervisors of mechanics, installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Installation, maintenance, etc/Supervisors of installation, maintenance, etc/First-line supervisors of mechanics, installers, etc/Mining machine operators, all other
Def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of mechanics, installers, and repairers. May also advise customers on recommended services. Excludes team or work leaders.

Level2: Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Installation, maintenance, etc/Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc/Computer, automated teller, etc/Mining machine operators, all other
Def: Repair, maintain, or install computers, word processing systems, automated teller machines, and electronic office machines, such as duplicating and fax machines.

title: Radio & telecommunications equipment installers & repairers
Level2: Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Installation, maintenance, etc/Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc/Radio & telecommunications equipment installers & repairers/Mining machine operators, all other

Level2: Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Installation, maintenance, etc/Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc/Radio & telecommunications equipment installers & repairers/Radio, cellular, etc

title: Telecommunications equipment installers & repairers, except line installers
ttl: Telecommunications equipment installers & repairers, except line installers
Level4: Telecommunications equipment installers & repairers, except line installers
Level2: Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Installation, maintenance, etc/Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc/Radio & telecommunications equipment installers & repairers/Telecommunications equipment installers & repairers, except line installers
Def: Install, set up, rearrange, or remove switching, distribution, routing, and dialing equipment used in central offices or headends. Service or repair telephone, cable television, Internet, and other communications equipment on customers’ property. May install communications equipment or communications wiring in buildings. Excludes “Telecommunications Line Installers and Repairers” (49-9052).

title: Miscellaneous electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, & repairers

Level3: Miscellaneous electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc

title: Avionics technicians
Level3: Miscellaneous electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
Level2: Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
pathString: Jobs/Installation, maintenance, etc/Electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc/Miscellaneous electrical & electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc/Avionics technicians
Def: Install, inspect, test, adjust, or repair avionics equipment, such as radar, radio, navigation, and missile control systems in aircraft or space vehicles.

Def: Operate or tend heating equipment other than basic metal, plastic, or food processing equipment. Includes activities such as annealing glass, drying lumber, curing rubber, removing moisture from materials, or boiling soap.

title: Inspectors, testers, sorters, samplers, & weighers
Level4: Cutting & slicing machine setters, operators, etc
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Inspectors, testers, etc/Cutting & slicing machine setters, operators, etc
Def: Inspect, test, sort, sample, or weigh nonagricultural raw materials or processed, machined, fabricated, or assembled parts or products for defects, wear, and deviations from specifications. May use precision measuring instruments and complex test equipment.

title: Jewelers & precious stone & metal workers
Level4: Cutting & slicing machine setters, operators, etc
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Jewelers & precious stone & metal workers/Cutting & slicing machine setters, operators, etc
Def: Design, fabricate, adjust, repair, or appraise jewelry, gold, silver, other precious metals, or gems. Includes diamond polishers and gem cutters, and persons who perform precision casting and modeling of molds, casting metal in molds, or setting precious and semiprecious stones for jewelry and related products.

title: Medical, dental, & ophthalmic laboratory technicians
Level4: Cutting & slicing machine setters, operators, etc
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Medical, dental, etc/Cutting & slicing machine setters, operators, etc

title: Dental laboratory technicians
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Medical, dental, etc/Dental laboratory technicians
Def: Construct and repair full or partial dentures or dental appliances. Excludes “Dental Assistants” (31-9091).

title: Medical appliance technicians
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Medical, dental, etc/Medical appliance technicians
Def: Construct, maintain, or repair medical supportive devices such as braces, orthotics and prosthetic devices, joints, arch supports, and other surgical and medical appliances.

title: Ophthalmic laboratory technicians
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Medical, dental, etc/Ophthalmic laboratory technicians
Def: Cut, grind, and polish eyeglasses, contact lenses, or other precision optical elements. Assemble and mount lenses into frames or process other optical elements. Includes precision lens polishers or grinders, centerer-edgers, and lens mounters. Excludes “Opticians, Dispensing ” (29-2081).

title: Packaging & filling machine operators & tenders
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Packaging & filling machine operators & tenders/Ophthalmic laboratory technicians
Def: Operate or tend machines to prepare industrial or consumer products for storage or shipment. Includes cannery workers who pack food products.

title: Painting workers
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Painting workers/Ophthalmic laboratory technicians

title: Coating, painting, & spraying machine setters, operators, & tenders
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Painting workers/Coating, painting, etc
Def: Set up, operate, or tend spraying or rolling machines to coat or paint any of a wide variety of products, including glassware, cloth, ceramics, metal, plastic, paper, or wood, with lacquer, silver, copper, rubber, varnish, glaze, enamel, oil, or rust-proofing materials. Includes painters of transportation vehicles such as painters in auto body repair facilities. Excludes “Plating Machine Setters, Operators, and Tenders, Metal and Plastic” (51-4193).

title: Painters, transportation equipment
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Painting workers/Painters, transportation equipment

title: Painting, coating, & decorating workers
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Painting workers/Painting, coating, etc
Def: Paint, coat, or decorate articles, such as furniture, glass, plateware, pottery, jewelry, toys, books, or leather. Excludes “Artists and Related Workers" (27-1010), “Designers” (27-1020), “Photographic Process Workers and Processing Machine Operators” (51-9151), and “Etchers and Engravers” (51-9194).

title: Semiconductor processors
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Semiconductor processors/Painting, coating, etc

title: Photographic process workers & processing machine operators
ttl: Photographic process workers & processing machine operators
Level3: Photographic process workers & processing machine operators
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Photographic process workers & processing machine operators/Painting, coating, etc
Def: Perform work involved in developing and processing photographic images from film or digital media. May perform precision tasks such as editing photographic negatives and prints.

title: Miscellaneous production workers
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Painting, coating, etc

title: Adhesive bonding machine operators & tenders
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Adhesive bonding machine operators & tenders
Def: Operate or tend bonding machines that use adhesives to join items for further processing or to form a completed product. Processes include joining veneer sheets into plywood; gluing paper; or joining rubber and rubberized fabric parts, plastic, simulated leather, or other materials. Excludes “Shoe Machine Operators and Tenders” (51-6042).

title: Cleaning, washing, & metal pickling equipment operators & tenders
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Cleaning, washing, etc
Def: Operate or tend machines to wash or clean products, such as barrels or kegs, glass items, tin plate, food, pulp, coal, plastic, or rubber, to remove impurities.

title: Cooling & freezing equipment operators & tenders
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Cooling & freezing equipment operators & tenders
Def: Operate or tend equipment such as cooling and freezing units, refrigerators, batch freezers, and freezing tunnels, to cool or freeze products, food, blood plasma, and chemicals.

title: Etchers & engravers
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Etchers & engravers
Def: Engrave or etch metal, wood, rubber, or other materials. Includes such workers as etcher-circuit processors, pantograph engravers, and silk screen etchers. Photoengravers are included in “Prepress Technicians and Workers” (51-5111).

title: Molders, shapers, & casters, except metal & plastic
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Molders, shapers, etc
Def: Mold, shape, form, cast, or carve products such as food products, figurines, tile, pipes, and candles consisting of clay, glass, plaster, concrete, stone, or combinations of materials.

title: Paper goods machine setters, operators, & tenders
ttl: Paper goods machine setters, operators, etc
Level4: Paper goods machine setters, operators, etc
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Paper goods machine setters, operators, etc
Def: Set up, operate, or tend paper goods machines that perform a variety of functions, such as converting, sawing, corrugating, banding, wrapping, boxing, stitching, forming, or sealing paper or paperboard sheets into products.

title: Tire builders
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Tire builders
Def: Operate machines to build tires.

title: Helpers--production workers
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Helpers--production workers
Def: Help production workers by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include supplying or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Apprentice workers are classified in the appropriate production occupations (51-0000).

title: Production workers, all other
pathString: Jobs/Production occupations/Other production occupations/Miscellaneous production workers/Production workers, all other
Def: All production workers not listed separately. Excludes “Packers and Packagers, Hand” (53-7064).
